<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The characteristic striking colour pattern of this species (i.e., T1-4 each anteriorly yellow-brown and posteriorly dark brown, as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Enicospilus abdominalis (Szepligeti, 1906) ♀ from Japan A habitus B head, frontal view C head, dorsal view D head, lateral view E mesosoma, lateral view F central part of fore wing." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.990.55542.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473775" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9A</figureCitation>
) is the most useful diagnostic character among the Japanese species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Enicospilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Enicospilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Enicospilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Some non-Japanese species, such as 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. zebrus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="zebrus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. zebrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Gauld &amp; Mitchell, 1981, have a similar colour pattern, but 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. abdominalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="abdominalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. abdominalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguishable by many characters, such as shape and size of fore wing fenestra and sclerites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species has been confused with 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. nigropectus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigropectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. nigropectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by many authors (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gauld, ID" journalOrPublisher="CAB: Slough / Commonwealth Institute of Entomology, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B41" refString="Gauld, ID, Mitchell, PA, 1981. The taxonomy, distribution and host preferences of Indo-Papuan parasitic wasps of the subfamily Ophioninae. CAB: Slough / Commonwealth Institute of Entomology, London" title="The taxonomy, distribution and host preferences of Indo-Papuan parasitic wasps of the subfamily Ophioninae." year="1981">Gauld and Mitchell (1981)</bibRefCitation>
) but is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. nigropectus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigropectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. nigropectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by presence of central sclerite of fore wing fenestra, as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Enicospilus abdominalis (Szepligeti, 1906) ♀ from Japan A habitus B head, frontal view C head, dorsal view D head, lateral view E mesosoma, lateral view F central part of fore wing." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.990.55542.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473775" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9F</figureCitation>
(central sclerite absent in 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. nigropectus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigropectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. nigropectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Enicospilus nigropectus Cameron, 1905 ♀ from Japan A habitus B head, frontal view C head, dorsal view D head, lateral view E mesosoma, lateral view F central part of fore wing." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.990.55542.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473799" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33F</figureCitation>
), larger value of SDI (1.3-1.4 in this species, as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Enicospilus abdominalis (Szepligeti, 1906) ♀ from Japan A habitus B head, frontal view C head, dorsal view D head, lateral view E mesosoma, lateral view F central part of fore wing." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.990.55542.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473775" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9F</figureCitation>
, but 0.9-1.1 in 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. nigropectus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigropectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. nigropectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Enicospilus nigropectus Cameron, 1905 ♀ from Japan A habitus B head, frontal view C head, dorsal view D head, lateral view E mesosoma, lateral view F central part of fore wing." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.990.55542.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473799" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33F</figureCitation>
), yellowish interocellar area (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Enicospilus abdominalis (Szepligeti, 1906) ♀ from Japan A habitus B head, frontal view C head, dorsal view D head, lateral view E mesosoma, lateral view F central part of fore wing." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.990.55542.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473775" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9B, C</figureCitation>
) (interocellar area usually blackish in 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. nigropectus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigropectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. nigropectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Enicospilus nigropectus Cameron, 1905 ♀ from Japan A habitus B head, frontal view C head, dorsal view D head, lateral view E mesosoma, lateral view F central part of fore wing." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.990.55542.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473799" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33B, C</figureCitation>
), etc. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Szepligeti" baseAuthorityYear="1906" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Enicospilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Enicospilus abdominalis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abdominalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Enicospilus abdominalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. signativentris" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="signativentris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. signativentris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be distinguished by striking colour pattern and absence of distinct posterior transverse carina of propodeum.
</paragraph>
